body:
I am seeing a somewhat alarming bug which I think is caused by some invalid operation performed by Verilator when it generates 8-bit math in the verilated C++. I'm using Verilator version 5.018 2023-10-30 on an arm64 platform. I looked at the slew of bugs reported recently in this area (Github issues 3824, 4709, 4832, 4837, 4841, 4842) but I did not find that any of the recommended "-fno-*" flags had any effect.

To focus just on the 1 line which I have determined is causing the issue with Verilator, see the following section of code. The calculation of d_bytes_next is more complicated than shown, but it should be clear that changing `d_bytes` to *any width greater than or equal to* the width of `d_bytes_next` should have absolutely no effect, since it will truncate to 4 bits in the first line of the always_comb block (`d_bytes_next = d_bytes;`) and it will width-expand with zero padding on the left when it is assigned to d_bytes in the always_ff block (`d_bytes <= d_bytes_next;`).

```verilog
  logic [3:0] d_bytes = '0;  // THIS DOES NOT WORK: d_bytes takes value 0x0 when it should not!
  // logic [7:0] d_bytes = '0;  // THIS DOES NOT WORK
  // logic [11:0] d_bytes = '0;  // THIS FIXES THE PROBLEM, EVEN THOUGH ONLY 4 BITS ARE NECESSARY
  // logic [8:0] d_bytes = '0;  // THIS FIXES THE PROBLEM ALSO, SUGGESTING 8-BIT VERILATOR MATH IS WRONG

  logic [3:0] d_bytes_next;

  always_ff @(posedge clk) begin
    if (reset) begin
      d_bytes <= '0;
    end else begin
      d_bytes <= d_bytes_next;
  end

  always_comb begin
    d_bytes_next = d_bytes;
   // additional logic that modifies d_bytes_next
  end
```

However, I found that the simulation shows that `d_bytes` is sometimes taking value `'0` when it should not! Specifically, it seems to do this if the width of `d_bytes` is less than or equal to 8 bits. This suggests there is a bug in the way Verilator performs 8-bit math (and 4-bit math, and any width less than or equal to 8-bit).

A screenshot is below showing that it *sometimes incorrectly takes the value of zero* when `d_bytes` is 4 bits wide, even though reset is not asserted and `d_bytes_next` is not zero.

<img width="699" alt="image" src="https://github.com/verilator/verilator/assets/63216497/a3d87b31-779c-40e6-b46c-1c836aab746e">

When I increase the width of `d_bytes` (unnecessarily) to something wider than 8-bits, then it works. There is no other change in the code; I've found that this is the only line which has any effect.

<img width="701" alt="image" src="https://github.com/verilator/verilator/assets/63216497/ea1290fd-998d-42d1-8066-369a32b2797d">

My suspicion is that there is some math operation which has been optimized out by Verilator (incorrectly), or else there is some fundamental 8-bit math logic bug where some variable is saturating or rolling over incorrectly in the C++ that Verilator generates.

Grepping around in the build directory, I also noticed that `d_bytes` is not declared as are all the other state variables. The variables `d_free` and `d_free_next` have similar declarations in the code, and yet they appear to have different CData declarations in the C++ that Verilator generates. I'm not sure if this is a valid lead or expected, but it does seem suspicious that Verilator is not declaring the exact state variable which is causing problems!

```c++
// Verilated -*- C++ -*-
// DESCRIPTION: Verilator output: Design internal header
// See Vtop.h for the primary calling header

#ifndef VERILATED_VTOP_AXIS_INSERT_BYTES_H_
#define VERILATED_VTOP_AXIS_INSERT_BYTES_H_  // guard

#include "verilated.h"
class Vtop__Syms;

class alignas(VL_CACHE_LINE_BYTES) Vtop_axis_insert_bytes final : public VerilatedModule {
  public:

    // DESIGN SPECIFIC STATE
    // Anonymous structures to workaround compiler member-count bugs
    struct {
        // ...
        // NOTICE THAT D_BYTES IS NOT DECLARED HERE!
        CData/*3:0*/ d_bytes_next;
        CData/*3:0*/ d_free;
        CData/*3:0*/ d_free_next;
        // ...
    };
    struct {
        // ...
        SData/*11:0*/ d_keep;
        SData/*11:0*/ d_keep_next;
        SData/*11:0*/ d_bytes;
        SData/*11:0*/ __Vdly__d_bytes;
        // ...
    };

    // INTERNAL VARIABLES
   // ...
};


#endif  // guard

```
